\f0\b Text:
\f1\b0 \
Welcome to 
\f2\i Talk OCD
\f1\i0 , a youth-led initiative under the HOSA Mental Health Promotion program. Our goal is to educate the public about Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD) and foster understanding through compassion, factual information, and open dialogue. We strive to create a community where individuals feel informed, supported, and empowered to discuss mental health without judgment.\
\

\f0\b 2. About Us
\f1\b0 \
\

\f0\b Who We Are
\f1\b0 \
We are a group of students from Bishop P. F. Reding Catholic Secondary School dedicated to promoting mental health awareness. As members of our school\'92s HOSA chapter, we focus on providing reliable, evidence-based information and encouraging open discussions about OCD among youth and the broader community.\
(Insert Team Photo)\

\f0\b \
Why We Chose OCD
\f1\b0 \
OCD is frequently misunderstood, often misrepresented in media and casual conversation. Misconceptions can create barriers to seeking help and support, especially for young people. We chose to focus on OCD to challenge stereotypes, raise awareness, and highlight the real impact this disorder can have on youth.\
\

\f0\b Our Mission
\f1\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	\'95	To educate the public with accurate and accessible information about OCD\
	\'95	To reduce stigma and misconceptions surrounding the disorder\
	\'95	To support youth mental health conversations in schools and communities\
	\'95	To empower individuals to understand OCD beyond stereotypes\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \

\f0\b 3. What Is OCD?
\f1\b0 \
\

\f0\b What OCD Actually Is
\f1\b0 \
Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD) is a mental health condition characterized by 
\f0\b obsessions
\f1\b0  and 
\f0\b compulsions
\f1\b0 :\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	\'95	
\f0\b Obsessions:
\f1\b0  Recurrent, intrusive, and unwanted thoughts, images, or urges that cause significant anxiety or distress.\
	\'95	
\f0\b Compulsions:
\f1\b0  Repetitive behaviours or mental acts performed in response to obsessions, often aimed at reducing anxiety.\
\
OCD can interfere with daily functioning, making school, work, and relationships challenging.\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Common Types of OCD
\f1\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	\'95	
\f0\b Contamination OCD:
\f1\b0  Fear of germs or dirt, leading to excessive cleaning or avoidance.\
	\'95	
\f0\b Checking OCD:
\f1\b0  Repeatedly verifying actions (e.g., locks, appliances) to prevent imagined harm.\
	\'95	
\f0\b Harm OCD:
\f1\b0  Intrusive fears of causing harm to oneself or others.\
	\'95	
\f0\b Symmetry/Ordering OCD:
\f1\b0  Strong need for objects or tasks to be perfectly aligned or symmetrical.\
	\'95	
\f0\b Relationship OCD:
\f1\b0  Obsessive doubts or concerns about romantic or interpersonal relationships.\
	\'95	
\f0\b Moral/Scrupulosity OCD:
\f1\b0  Intrusive thoughts related to morality, religion, or ethics, often causing guilt or shame.\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Who Can Have OCD?
\f1\b0 \
OCD can affect anyone, children, adolescents, and adults, and is not determined by personality, habits, or preferences. It is a legitimate mental health condition that requires understanding and, in many cases, professional support.\
\

\f0\b 4. The Reality of Living With OCD
\f1\b0 \
\

\f0\b Emotional Impact
\f1\b0 \
OCD can create significant emotional strain, including:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	\'95	Anxiety\
	\'95	Stress\
	\'95	Guilt\
	\'95	Fear\
	\'95	Exhaustion\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Daily Challenges
\f1\b0 \
Individuals with OCD often face practical difficulties in their daily lives, such as:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	\'95	Spending excessive time on compulsions\
	\'95	Difficulty focusing in school or work\
	\'95	Struggling with social relationships\
	\'95	Feeling misunderstood by peers, family, or teachers\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 The OCD Cycle
\f1\b0 \
OCD operates as a continuous cycle:\
\

\f0\b Obsessive Thought \uc0\u8594  Anxiety \u8594  Compulsion \u8594  Temporary Relief \u8594  Obsessive Thought Again
\f1\b0 \
